'''Snake venom''' is highly modified [[saliva]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Reptile Venom Research|url=http://www.reptilepark.com.au/venom_snake.asp|publisher=Australian Reptile Park|accessdate=21 December 2010}}</ref> containing [[zootoxin]]s used by [[snake]]s to immobilize and digest [[prey]] or to serve as a defence mechanism against a potential [[predator]] or other threat.  The venom produced by the snake's venom gland apparatus is delivered by an injection system of modified [[fang]]s that enable the venom to penetrate into the target.<ref name=Bauchot/>

The glands that secrete the zootoxins are a modification of the [[parotid gland|parotid salivary gland]] found in other [[vertebrates]] and are usually situated on each side of the head, below and behind the eye and encapsulated in a muscular sheath.  The glands have large [[alveoli]] in which the synthesized [[venom]] is stored before being conveyed by a duct to the base of channeled or tubular fangs through which it is ejected.<ref name=Firefly>{{cite book|last=(edited by) Halliday; Adler|first=Tim; Kraig|title=Firefly Encyclopedia of Reptiles and Amphibians|year=2002|publisher=Firefly Books Ltd.|location=Toronto, Canada|isbn=1-55297-613-0|pages=202–203}}</ref><ref name=JVenom/>

Venoms contain more than 20 different compounds, mostly proteins and polypeptides.<ref name=Firefly/> A complex mixture of proteins, enzymes, and various other substances with toxic and lethal properties<ref name=Bauchot/> serves to immobilize the prey animal,<ref name=Mattison>{{cite book|last=Mattison|first=Chris|title=The New Encyclopedia of Snakes|year=2007 (first published in 1995)|publisher=Princeton University Press (Princeton and Oxford) first published in Blandford|location=New Jersey, USA (first published in the UK)|isbn=0-691-13295-X|page=117}}</ref> enzymes play an important role in the digestion of prey,<ref name=JVenom>{{cite journal|last=Bottrall|first=Joshua L.|coauthors=Frank Madaras, Christopher D Biven, Michael G Venning, and Peter J Mirtschin|title=Proteolytic activity of Elapid and Viperid Snake venoms and its implication to digestion|journal=Journal of Venom Research|date=30|year=2010|month=September|volume=1|issue=3|pages=18–28|pmid=21544178|accessdate=26 December 2011|pmc=3086185}}</ref> and various other substances are responsible for important but non-lethal biological effects.<ref name=Bauchot>{{cite book|last=(Edited by) Bauchot|first=Roland|title=Snakes: A Natural History|year=1994|publisher=Sterling Publishing Co., Inc.|location=New York City, NY, USA|isbn=1-4027-3181-7|pages=194–209}}</ref> Some of the proteins in snake venom have very specific effects on various biological functions including blood coagulation, blood pressure regulation, transmission of the nervous or muscular impulse and have been developed for use as pharmacological or diagnostic tools or even useful drugs.<ref name=Bauchot/>

== Chemistry ==
[[Charles Lucien Bonaparte]], the son of [[Lucien Bonaparte]], younger brother of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]], was the first to establish the proteinaceous nature of snake venom in 1843.

[[Proteins]] constitute 90-95% of venom's dry weight and they are responsible for almost all of its biological effects. Among hundreds, even thousands of proteins found in venom, there are toxins, [[neurotoxin]]s in particular, as well as nontoxic proteins (which also have pharmacological properties), and many enzymes, especially hydrolytic ones.<ref name=Bauchot/> Enzymes ([[Molecular mass|molecular weight]] 13-150 KDa) make-up 80-90% of viperid and 25-70% of elapid venoms: digestive hydrolases, L-amino acid oxidase, phospholipases, thrombin-like pro-coagulant, and kallikrein-like serine proteases and [[metalloproteinases]] (hemorrhagins), which damage vascular endothelium. [[Polypeptide]] toxins (molecular weight 5-10 KDa) include [[cytotoxin]]s, [[cardiotoxin]]s, and postsynaptic neurotoxins (such as [[Alpha-Bungarotoxin|α-bungarotoxin]] and [[Cobratoxin|α-Cobratoxin]]), which bind to [[acetylcholine receptor]]s at neuromuscular junctions. Compounds with low molecular weight (up to 1.5 KDa) include metals, peptides, lipids, nucleosides, carbohydrates, amines, and oligopeptides, which inhibit angiotensin converting enzyme (ACE) and potentiate bradykinin (BPP). Inter- and intra-species variation in venom chemical composition is geographical and ontogenic.<ref name=Firefly/> [[Phosphodiesterase]]s interfere with the prey's cardiac system, mainly to lower the [[blood pressure]]. [[Phospholipase A2]] causes [[hemolysis]] by lysing the [[phospholipid]] [[cell membranes]] of [[red blood cells]].<ref name="pmid14124757">{{cite journal |author=CONDREA E, DEVRIES A, MAGER J |title=HEMOLYSIS AND SPLITTING OF HUMAN ERYTHROCYTE PHOSPHOLIPIDS BY SNAKE VENOMS |journal=Biochim. Biophys. Acta |volume=84 |issue= |pages=60–73 |year=1964 |month=February |pmid=14124757 |doi= |url=}}</ref> Amino acid [[oxidase]]s and [[protease]]s are used for digestion. Amino acid oxidase also triggers some other enzymes and is responsible for the yellow colour of the venom of some species. [[Hyaluronidase]] increases tissue permeability to accelerate absorption of other enzymes into tissues. Some snake venoms carry fasciculins, like the [[mamba]]s (''Dendroaspis''), which inhibit [[cholinesterase]] to make the prey lose muscle control.<ref name=Fasciculins>{{cite journal|last=Rodríguez-Ithurralde|first=D.|coauthors=R. Silveira, L. Barbeito, F. Dajas|title=Fasciculin, a powerful anticholinesterase polypeptide from Dendroaspis angusticeps venom|journal=Neurochemistry International|year=1983|volume=5|issue=3|pages=267–274|doi=10.1016/0197-0186(83)90028-1|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0197018683900281|accessdate=26 December 2011}}</ref>  

