Snake toxins vary greatly in their functions. Two major classifications of toxins found in snake venoms include [[neurotoxin]]s (mostly found in elapids) and [[hemotoxin]]s (mostly found in viperids). However, there are exceptions - an African spitting cobra [[Naja nigricollis]]'s venom consists mainly of hemotoxins, while the [[Mojave rattlesnake]]'s venom is primarily neurotoxic. However, there are numerous other different types of toxins which both elapids or viperids may carry. 

